# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flow-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Flow measurement methods other than positive-displacement flowmeters rely on forces produced by the flowing stream as it overcomes a known constriction, to indirectly calculate flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Flow may be measured by measuring the velocity of fluid over a known area.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] For very large flows, tracer methods may be used to deduce the flow rate from the change in concentration of a dye or radioisotope.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Both gas and liquid flow can be measured in physical quantities of kind volumetric flow rate or mass flow rates, with respective SI units such as cubic meters per second or kilograms per second, respectively.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] These measurements are related by the material's density.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The density of a liquid is almost independent of conditions.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This is not the case for gases, the densities of which depend greatly upon pressure, temperature and to a lesser extent, composition.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] When gases or liquids are transferred for their energy content, as in the sale of natural gas, the flow rate may also be expressed in terms of energy flow, such as gigajoule per hour or BTU per day.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The energy flow rate is the volumetric flow rate multiplied by the energy content per unit volume or mass flow rate multiplied by the energy content per unit mass.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Energy flow rate is usually derived from mass or volumetric flow rate by the use of a flow computer.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] In engineering contexts, the volumetric flow rate is usually given the symbol Q , and the mass flow rate, the symbol ${\dot {m}}$ .
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] For a fluid having density $\rho$ , mass and volumetric flow rates may be related by ${\dot {m}}=\rho Q$ .
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Gases are compressible and change volume when placed under pressure, are heated or are cooled.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A volume of gas under one set of pressure and temperature conditions is not equivalent to the same gas under different conditions.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Gas *mass* flow rate can be directly measured, independent of pressure and temperature effects, with ultrasonic flow meters, thermal mass flowmeters, Coriolis mass flowmeters, or mass flow controllers.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] For liquids, various units are used depending upon the application and industry, but might include gallons (U.S. or imperial) per minute, liters per second, liters per m2 per hour, bushels per minute or, when describing river flows, cumecs (cubic meters per second) or acre-feet per day.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] In oceanography a common unit to measure volume transport (volume of water transported by a current for example) is a sverdrup (Sv) equivalent to 106 m3/s.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A primary flow element is a device inserted into the flowing fluid that produces a physical property that can be accurately related to flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] For example, an orifice plate produces a pressure drop that is a function of the square of the volume rate of flow through the orifice.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A vortex meter primary flow element produces a series of oscillations of pressure.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Generally, the physical property generated by the primary flow element is more convenient to measure than the flow itself.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The properties of the primary flow element, and the fidelity of the practical installation to the assumptions made in calibration, are critical factors in the accuracy of the flow measurement.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A positive displacement meter may be compared to a bucket and a stopwatch.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The stopwatch is started when the flow starts and stopped when the bucket reaches its limit.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The volume divided by the time gives the flow rate.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] For continuous measurements, we need a system of continually filling and emptying buckets to divide the flow without letting it out of the pipe.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] These continuously forming and collapsing volumetric displacements may take the form of pistons reciprocating in cylinders, gear teeth mating against the internal wall of a meter or through a progressive cavity created by rotating oval gears or a helical screw.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Because they are used for domestic water measurement, piston meters, also known as rotary piston or semi-positive displacement meters, are the most common flow measurement devices in the UK and are used for almost all meter sizes up to and including 40 mm (1+1⁄2 in).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The piston meter operates on the principle of a piston rotating within a chamber of known volume.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] For each rotation, an amount of water passes through the piston chamber.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Through a gear mechanism and, sometimes, a magnetic drive, a needle dial and odometer type display are advanced.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] An oval gear meter is a positive displacement meter that uses two or more oblong gears configured to rotate at right angles to one another, forming a T shape.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Such a meter has two sides, which can be called A and B.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] No fluid passes through the center of the meter, where the teeth of the two gears always mesh.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] On one side of the meter (A), the teeth of the gears close off the fluid flow because the elongated gear on side A is protruding into the measurement chamber, while on the other side of the meter (B), a cavity holds a fixed volume of fluid in a measurement chamber.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] As the fluid pushes the gears, it rotates them, allowing the fluid in the measurement chamber on side B to be released into the outlet port.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Meanwhile, fluid entering the inlet port will be driven into the measurement chamber of side A, which is now open.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The teeth on side B will now close off the fluid from entering side B.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This cycle continues as the gears rotate and fluid is metered through alternating measurement chambers.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Permanent magnets in the rotating gears can transmit a signal to an electric reed switch or current transducer for flow measurement.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Though claims for high performance are made, they are generally not as precise as the sliding vane design.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Gear meters differ from oval gear meters in that the measurement chambers are made up of the gaps between the teeth of the gears.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] These openings divide up the fluid stream and as the gears rotate away from the inlet port, the meter's inner wall closes off the chamber to hold the fixed amount of fluid.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The outlet port is located in the area where the gears are coming back together.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The fluid is forced out of the meter as the gear teeth mesh and reduce the available pockets to nearly zero volume.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Helical gear flowmeters get their name from the shape of their gears or rotors.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] These rotors resemble the shape of a helix, which is a spiral-shaped structure.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] As the fluid flows through the meter, it enters the compartments in the rotors, causing the rotors to rotate.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The length of the rotor is sufficient that the inlet and outlet are always separated from each other thus blocking a free flow of liquid.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The mating helical rotors create a progressive cavity which opens to admit fluid, seals itself off and then opens up to the downstream side to release the fluid.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This happens in a continuous fashion and the flowrate is calculated from the speed of rotation.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This is the most commonly used measurement system for measuring water supply in houses.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The fluid, most commonly water, enters in one side of the meter and strikes the nutating disk, which is eccentrically mounted.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The disk must then "wobble" or nutate about the vertical axis, since the bottom and the top of the disk remain in contact with the mounting chamber.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A partition separates the inlet and outlet chambers.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] As the disk nutates, it gives direct indication of the volume of the liquid that has passed through the meter as volumetric flow is indicated by a gearing and register arrangement, which is connected to the disk.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] It is reliable for flow measurements within 1 percent.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The turbine flowmeter (better described as an axial turbine) translates the mechanical action of the turbine rotating in the liquid flow around an axis into a user-readable rate of flow (gpm, lpm, etc.).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The turbine tends to have all the flow traveling around it.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The turbine wheel is set in the path of a fluid stream.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The flowing fluid impinges on the turbine blades, imparting a force to the blade surface and setting the rotor in motion.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] When a steady rotation speed has been reached, the speed is proportional to fluid velocity.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Turbine flowmeters are used for the measurement of natural gas and liquid flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Turbine meters are less accurate than displacement and jet meters at low flow rates, but the measuring element does not occupy or severely restrict the entire path of flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The flow direction is generally straight through the meter, allowing for higher flow rates and less pressure loss than displacement-type meters.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] They are the meter of choice for large commercial users, fire protection, and as master meters for the water distribution system.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Strainers are generally required to be installed in front of the meter to protect the measuring element from gravel or other debris that could enter the water distribution system.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Turbine meters are generally available for 4 to 30 cm (1+1⁄2–12 in) or higher pipe sizes.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Turbine meter bodies are commonly made of stainless steel, bronze, cast Iron, or ductile iron.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Internal turbine elements can be plastic or non-corrosive metal alloys.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] They are accurate in normal working conditions but are greatly affected by the flow profile and fluid conditions.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Turbine flowmeters are commonly best suited for low viscosity, as large particulate can damage the rotor.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] When choosing a meter for an application that requires particulate flowing through the pipe, it is best to use a meter without moving parts such as a Magnetic flowmeters.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Fire meters are a specialized type of turbine meter with approvals for the high flow rates required in fire protection systems.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] They are often approved by Underwriters Laboratories (UL) or Factory Mutual (FM) or similar authorities for use in fire protection.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Portable turbine meters may be temporarily installed to measure water used from a fire hydrant.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The meters are normally made of aluminum to be lightweight, and are usually 7.5 cm (3 in) capacity.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Water utilities often require them for measurement of water used in construction, pool filling, or where a permanent meter is not yet installed.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The Woltman meter (invented by Reinhard Woltman in the 19th century) comprises a rotor with helical blades inserted axially in the flow, much like a ducted fan; it can be considered a type of turbine flowmeter.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] They are commonly referred to as helix meters, and are popular at larger sizes.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A single jet meter consists of a simple impeller with radial vanes, impinged upon by a single jet.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] They are increasing in popularity in the UK at larger sizes and are commonplace in the EU.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Paddle wheel flowmeters (also known as Pelton wheel sensors) consist of three primary components: the paddle wheel sensor, the pipe fitting and the display/controller.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The paddle wheel sensor consists of a freely rotating wheel/impeller with embedded magnets which are perpendicular to the flow and will rotate when inserted in the flowing medium.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] As the magnets in the blades spin past the sensor, the paddle wheel meter generates a frequency and voltage signal which is proportional to the flow rate.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The faster the flow the higher the frequency and the voltage output.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The paddle wheel meter is designed to be inserted into a pipe fitting, either 'in-line' or insertion style.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Similarly to turbine meters, the paddle wheel meter requires a minimum run of straight pipe before and after the sensor.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Flow displays and controllers are used to receive the signal from the paddle wheel meter and convert it into actual flow rate or total flow values.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A multiple jet or multijet meter is a velocity type meter which has an impeller which rotates horizontally on a vertical shaft.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The impeller element is in a housing in which multiple inlet ports direct the fluid flow at the impeller causing it to rotate in a specific direction in proportion to the flow velocity.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This meter works mechanically much like a single jet meter except that the ports direct the flow at the impeller equally from several points around the circumference of the element, not just one point; this minimizes uneven wear on the impeller and its shaft.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Thus, these types of meters are recommended to be installed horizontally with its roller index pointing skywards.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The Pelton wheel turbine (better described as a radial turbine) translates the mechanical action of the Pelton wheel rotating in the liquid flow around an axis into a user-readable rate of flow (gpm, lpm, etc.).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The Pelton wheel tends to have all the flow traveling around it with the inlet flow focused on the blades by a jet.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Flow through a large penstock such as used at a hydroelectric power plant can be measured by averaging the flow velocity over the entire area.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Propeller-type current meters (similar to the purely mechanical Ekman current meter, but now with electronic data acquisition) can be traversed over the area of the penstock and velocities averaged to calculate total flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This may be on the order of hundreds of cubic meters per second.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The flow must be kept steady during the traverse of the current meters.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Methods for testing hydroelectric turbines are given in IEC standard 41.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Such flow measurements are often commercially important when testing the efficiency of large turbines.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] There are several types of flowmeter that rely on Bernoulli's principle.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The pressure is measured either by using laminar plates, an orifice, a nozzle, or a Venturi tube to create an artificial constriction and then measure the pressure loss of fluids as they pass that constriction, or by measuring static and stagnation pressures to derive the dynamic pressure.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A Venturi meter constricts the flow in some fashion, and pressure sensors measure the differential pressure before and within the constriction.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This method is widely used to measure flow rate in the transmission of gas through pipelines, and has been used since Roman Empire times.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The coefficient of discharge of Venturi meter ranges from 0.93 to 0.97.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The first large-scale Venturi meters to measure liquid flows were developed by Clemens Herschel, who used them to measure small and large flows of water and wastewater beginning at the very end of the 19th century.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] An orifice plate is a plate with a hole through it, placed perpendicular to the flow; it constricts the flow, and measuring the pressure differential across the constriction gives the flow rate.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] It is basically a crude form of Venturi meter, but with higher energy losses.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] There are three type of orifice: concentric, eccentric, and segmental.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The Dall tube is a shortened version of a Venturi meter, with a lower pressure drop than an orifice plate.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] As with these flowmeters the flow rate in a Dall tube is determined by measuring the pressure drop caused by restriction in the conduit.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The pressure differential is typically measured using diaphragm pressure transducers with digital readout.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Since these meters have significantly lower permanent pressure losses than orifice meters, Dall tubes are widely used for measuring the flow rate of large pipeworks.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Differential pressure produced by a Dall tube is higher than Venturi tube and nozzle, all of them having same throat diameters.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A pitot tube is used to measure fluid flow velocity.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The tube is pointed into the flow and the difference between the stagnation pressure at the tip of the probe and the static pressure at its side is measured, yielding the dynamic pressure from which the fluid velocity is calculated using Bernoulli's equation.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A volumetric rate of flow may be determined by measuring the velocity at different points in the flow and generating the velocity profile.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Averaging pitot tubes (also called impact probes) extend the theory of pitot tube to more than one dimension.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A typical averaging pitot tube consists of three or more holes (depending on the type of probe) on the measuring tip arranged in a specific pattern.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] More holes allow the instrument to measure the direction of the flow velocity in addition to its magnitude (after appropriate calibration).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Three holes arranged in a line allow the pressure probes to measure the velocity vector in two dimensions.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Introduction of more holes, e.g. five holes arranged in a "plus" formation, allow measurement of the three-dimensional velocity vector.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Cone meters are a newer differential pressure metering device first launched in 1985 by McCrometer in Hemet, CA.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The cone meter is a generic yet robust differential pressure (DP) meter that has shown to be resistant to effects of asymmetric and swirling flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] While working with the same basic principles as Venturi and orifice type DP meters, cone meters don't require the same upstream and downstream piping.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The cone acts as a conditioning device as well as a differential pressure producer.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Upstream requirements are between 0–5 diameters compared to up to 44 diameters for an orifice plate or 22 diameters for a Venturi.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Because cone meters are generally of welded construction, it is recommended they are always calibrated prior to service.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Inevitably heat effects of welding cause distortions and other effects that prevent tabular data on discharge coefficients with respect to line size, beta ratio and operating Reynolds numbers from being collected and published.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Calibrated cone meters have an uncertainty up to ±0.5%.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Linear resistance meters, also called laminar flowmeters, measure very low flows at which the measured differential pressure is linearly proportional to the flow and to the fluid viscosity.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Such flow is called viscous drag flow or laminar flow, as opposed to the turbulent flow measured by orifice plates, Venturis and other meters mentioned in this section, and is characterized by Reynolds numbers below 2000.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The primary flow element may consist of a single long capillary tube, a bundle of such tubes, or a long porous plug; such low flows create small pressure differentials but longer flow elements create higher, more easily measured differentials.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] These flowmeters are particularly sensitive to temperature changes affecting the fluid viscosity and the diameter of the flow element, as can be seen in the governing Hagen–Poiseuille equation.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A "variable area meter" measures fluid flow by allowing the cross sectional area of the device to vary in response to the flow, causing some measurable effect that indicates the rate.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A rotameter is an example of a variable area meter, where a weighted "float" rises in a tapered tube as the flow rate increases; the float stops rising when area between float and tube is large enough that the weight of the float is balanced by the drag of fluid flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A kind of rotameter used for medical gases is the Thorpe tube flowmeter.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Floats are made in many different shapes, with spheres and spherical ellipses being the most common.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Some are designed to spin visibly in the fluid stream to aid the user in determining whether the float is stuck or not.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Rotameters are available for a wide range of liquids but are most commonly used with water or air.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] They can be made to reliably measure flow down to 1% accuracy.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Another type is a variable area orifice, where a spring-loaded tapered plunger is deflected by flow through an orifice.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The displacement can be related to the flow rate.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Optical flowmeters use light to determine flow rate.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Small particles which accompany natural and industrial gases pass through two laser beams focused a short distance apart in the flow path in a pipe by illuminating optics.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Laser light is scattered when a particle crosses the first beam.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The detecting optics collects scattered light on a photodetector, which then generates a pulse signal.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] As the same particle crosses the second beam, the detecting optics collect scattered light on a second photodetector, which converts the incoming light into a second electrical pulse.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] By measuring the time interval between these pulses, the gas velocity is calculated as $V=D/t$ where D is the distance between the laser beams and t is the time interval.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Laser-based optical flowmeters measure the actual speed of particles, a property which is not dependent on thermal conductivity of gases, variations in gas flow or composition of gases.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The operating principle enables optical laser technology to deliver highly accurate flow data, even in challenging environments which may include high temperature, low flow rates, high pressure, high humidity, pipe vibration and acoustic noise.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Optical flowmeters are very stable with no moving parts and deliver a highly repeatable measurement over the life of the product.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Because distance between the two laser sheets does not change, optical flowmeters do not require periodic calibration after their initial commissioning.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Optical flowmeters require only one installation point, instead of the two installation points typically required by other types of meters.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A single installation point is simpler, requires less maintenance and is less prone to errors.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Commercially available optical flowmeters are capable of measuring flow from 0.1 m/s to faster than 100 m/s (1000:1 turn down ratio) and have been demonstrated to be effective for the measurement of flare gases from oil wells and refineries, a contributor to atmospheric pollution.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Open channel flow describes cases where flowing liquid has a top surface open to the air; the cross-section of the flow is only determined by the shape of the channel on the lower side, and is variable depending on the depth of liquid in the channel.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Techniques appropriate for a fixed cross-section of flow in a pipe are not useful in open channels.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Measuring flow in waterways is an important open-channel flow application; such installations are known as stream gauges.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The level of the water is measured at a designated point behind weir or in flume using various secondary devices (bubblers, ultrasonic, float, and differential pressure are common methods).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The flow rate can then be integrated over time into volumetric flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Level to flow devices are commonly used to measure the flow of surface waters (springs, streams, and rivers), industrial discharges, and sewage.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Of these, weirs are used on flow streams with low solids (typically surface waters), while flumes are used on flows containing low or high solids contents.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The cross-sectional area of the flow is calculated from a depth measurement and the average velocity of the flow is measured directly (Doppler and propeller methods are common).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Velocity times the cross-sectional area yields a flow rate which can be integrated into volumetric flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] There are two types of area velocity flowmeter: (1) wetted; and (2) non-contact.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Wetted area velocity sensors have to be typically mounted on the bottom of a channel or river and use Doppler to measure the velocity of the entrained particles.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] With depth and a programmed cross-section this can then provide discharge flow measurement.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Non-contact devices that use laser or radar are mounted above the channel and measure the velocity from above and then use ultrasound to measure the depth of the water from above.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Radar devices can only measure surface velocities, whereas laser-based devices can measure velocities sub-surface.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A known amount of dye (or salt) per unit time is added to a flow stream.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] After complete mixing, the concentration is measured.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Acoustic Doppler velocimetry (ADV) is designed to record instantaneous velocity components at a single point with a relatively high frequency.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Measurements are performed by measuring the velocity of particles in a remote sampling volume based upon the Doppler shift effect.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Thermal mass flowmeters generally use combinations of heated elements and temperature sensors to measure the difference between static and flowing heat transfer to a fluid and infer its flow with a knowledge of the fluid's specific heat and density.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The fluid temperature is also measured and compensated for.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] If the density and specific heat characteristics of the fluid are constant, the meter can provide a direct mass flow readout, and does not need any additional pressure temperature compensation over their specified range.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Technological progress has allowed the manufacture of thermal mass flowmeters on a microscopic scale as MEMS sensors; these flow devices can be used to measure flow rates in the range of nanoliters or microliters per minute.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Thermal mass flowmeter (also called thermal dispersion or thermal displacement flowmeter) technology is used for compressed air, nitrogen, helium, argon, oxygen, and natural gas.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] In fact, most gases can be measured as long as they are fairly clean and non-corrosive.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] For more aggressive gases, the meter may be made out of special alloys (e.g.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Hastelloy), and pre-drying the gas also helps to minimize corrosion.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Today, thermal mass flowmeters are used to measure the flow of gases in a growing range of applications, such as chemical reactions or thermal transfer applications that are difficult for other flowmetering technologies.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Some other typical applications of flow sensors can be found in the medical field like, for example, CPAP devices, anesthesia equipment or respiratory devices.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This is because thermal mass flowmeters monitor variations in one or more of the thermal characteristics (temperature, thermal conductivity, and/or specific heat) of gaseous media to define the mass flow rate.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] In many late model automobiles, a Mass Airflow (MAF) sensor is used to accurately determine the mass flow rate of intake air used in the internal combustion engine.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Many such mass flow sensors use a heated element and a downstream temperature sensor to indicate the air flowrate.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] In either case, the vehicle's electronic control unit interprets the sensor signals as a real-time indication of an engine's fuel requirement.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Another method of flow measurement involves placing a bluff body (called a shedder bar) in the path of the fluid.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] As the fluid passes this bar, disturbances in the flow called vortices are created.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The vortices trail behind the cylinder, alternatively from each side of the bluff body.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This vortex trail is called the Von Kármán vortex street after von Kármán's 1912 mathematical description of the phenomenon.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The frequency at which these vortices alternate sides is essentially proportional to the flow rate of the fluid.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Inside, atop, or downstream of the shedder bar is a sensor for measuring the frequency of the vortex shedding.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This sensor is often a piezoelectric crystal, which produces a small, but measurable, voltage pulse every time a vortex is created.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Since the frequency of such a voltage pulse is also proportional to the fluid velocity, a volumetric flow rate is calculated using the cross-sectional area of the flowmeter.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Sonar flowmeters are non-intrusive clamp-on devices that measure flow in pipes conveying slurries, corrosive fluids, multiphase fluids and flows where insertion type flowmeters are not desired.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Sonar flowmeters have been widely adopted in mining, metals processing, and upstream oil and gas industries where traditional technologies have certain limitations due to their tolerance to various flow regimes and turn down ratios.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Sonar flowmeters have the capacity of measuring the velocity of liquids or gases non-intrusively within the pipe and then leverage this velocity measurement into a flow rate by using the cross-sectional area of the pipe and the line pressure and temperature.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The principle behind this flow measurement is the use of underwater acoustics.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Likewise, sonar flow measurement uses the same techniques and algorithms employed in underwater acoustics, but applies them to flow measurement of oil and gas wells and flow lines.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Modern innovations in the measurement of flow rate incorporate electronic devices that can correct for varying pressure and temperature (i.e. density) conditions, non-linearities, and for the characteristics of the fluid.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Magnetic flowmeters, often called "mag meter"s or "electromag"s, use a magnetic field applied to the metering tube, which results in a potential difference proportional to the flow velocity perpendicular to the flux lines.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The potential difference is sensed by electrodes aligned perpendicular to the flow and the applied magnetic field.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The physical principle at work is Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The magnetic flowmeter requires a conducting fluid and a nonconducting pipe liner.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The electrodes must not corrode in contact with the process fluid; some magnetic flowmeters have auxiliary transducers installed to clean the electrodes in place.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The applied magnetic field is pulsed, which allows the flowmeter to cancel out the effect of stray voltage in the piping system.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A Lorentz force velocimetry system is called Lorentz force flowmeter (LFF).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] An LFF measures the integrated or bulk Lorentz force resulting from the interaction between a liquid metal in motion and an applied magnetic field.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] In this case, the characteristic length of the magnetic field is of the same order of magnitude as the dimensions of the channel.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] It must be addressed that in the case where localized magnetic fields are used, it is possible to perform local velocity measurements and thus the term Lorentz force velocimeter is used.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] There are two main types of ultrasonic flowmeters: Doppler and transit time.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] While they both utilize ultrasound to make measurements and can be non-invasive (measure flow from outside the tube, pipe or vessel, also called clamp-on device), they measure flow by very different methods.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Ultrasonic **transit time** flowmeters measure the difference of the transit time of ultrasonic pulses propagating in and against the direction of flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This time difference is a measure for the average velocity of the fluid along the path of the ultrasonic beam.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] By using the absolute transit times both the averaged fluid velocity and the speed of sound can be calculated.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] With wide-beam illumination transit time ultrasound can also be used to measure volume flow independent of the cross-sectional area of the vessel or tube.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Ultrasonic **Doppler**flowmeters measure the Doppler shift resulting from reflecting an ultrasonic beam off the particulates in flowing fluid.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The frequency of the transmitted beam is affected by the movement of the particles; this frequency shift can be used to calculate the fluid velocity.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] For the Doppler principle to work, there must be a high enough density of sonically reflective materials such as solid particles or air bubbles suspended in the fluid.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This is in direct contrast to an ultrasonic transit time flowmeter, where bubbles and solid particles reduce the accuracy of the measurement.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Due to the dependency on these particles, there are limited applications for Doppler flowmeters.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This technology is also known as acoustic Doppler velocimetry.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] One advantage of ultrasonic flowmeters is that they can effectively measure the flow rates for a wide variety of fluids, as long as the speed of sound through that fluid is known.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] For example, ultrasonic flowmeters are used for the measurement of such diverse fluids as liquid natural gas (LNG) and blood.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] One can also calculate the expected speed of sound for a given fluid; this can be compared to the speed of sound empirically measured by an ultrasonic flowmeter for the purposes of monitoring the quality of the flowmeter's measurements.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A drop in quality (change in the measured speed of sound) is an indication that the meter needs servicing.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Using the Coriolis effect that causes a laterally vibrating tube to distort, a direct measurement of mass flow can be obtained in a coriolis flowmeter.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Furthermore, a direct measure of the density of the fluid is obtained.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Coriolis measurement can be very accurate irrespective of the type of gas or liquid that is measured; the same measurement tube can be used for hydrogen gas and bitumen without recalibration.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Coriolis flowmeters can be used for the measurement of natural gas flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A beam of laser light impinging on a moving particle will be partially scattered with a change in wavelength proportional to the particle's speed (the Doppler effect).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A laser Doppler velocimeter (LDV), also called a laser Doppler anemometer (LDA), focuses a laser beam into a small volume in a flowing fluid containing small particles (naturally occurring or induced).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The particles scatter the light with a Doppler shift.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Analysis of this shifted wavelength can be used to directly, and with great precision, determine the speed of the particle and thus a close approximation of the fluid velocity.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A number of different techniques and device configurations are available for determining the Doppler shift.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] All use a photodetector (typically an avalanche photodiode) to convert the light into an electrical waveform for analysis.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] In most devices, the original laser light is divided into two beams.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] In one general LDV class, the two beams are made to intersect at their focal points where they interfere and generate a set of straight fringes.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The sensor is then aligned to the flow such that the fringes are perpendicular to the flow direction.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] As particles pass through the fringes, the Doppler-shifted light is collected into the photodetector.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] In another general LDV class, one beam is used as a reference and the other is Doppler-scattered.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Both beams are then collected onto the photodetector where optical heterodyne detection is used to extract the Doppler signal.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Even though ideally the flowmeter should be unaffected by its environment, in practice this is unlikely to be the case.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Often measurement errors originate from incorrect installation or other environment dependent factors.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] In situ methods are used when flowmeter is calibrated in the correct flow conditions.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The result of a flowmeter calibration will result in two related statistics: a performance indicator metric and a flow rate metric.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] For pipe flows a so-called transit time method is applied where a radiotracer is injected as a pulse into the measured flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The transit time is defined with the help of radiation detectors placed on the outside of the pipe.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The volume flow is obtained by multiplying the measured average fluid flow velocity by the inner pipe cross-section.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] This reference flow value is compared with the simultaneous flow value given by the flow measurement to be calibrated.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The procedure is standardised (ISO 2975/VII for liquids and BS 5857-2.4 for gases).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The best accredited measurement uncertainty for liquids and gases is 0.5%.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The radiotracer dilution method is used to calibrate open channel flow measurements.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] A solution with a known tracer concentration is injected at a constant known velocity into the channel flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Downstream the tracer solution is thoroughly mixed over the flow cross-section, a continuous sample is taken and its tracer concentration in relation to that of the injected solution is determined.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The flow reference value is determined by using the tracer balance condition between the injected tracer flow and the diluting flow.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The procedure is standardised (ISO 9555-1 and ISO 9555-2 for liquid flow in open channels).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The best accredited measurement uncertainty is 1%.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] Using the optical measuring method of laser Doppler velocimetry (LDV), the local flow velocities are measured on one (or possibly several) measuring paths along the pipe diameter (velocity profiles).
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The optical access to the fluid required for this is realized under operating conditions using the tapping method.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The measured values of the flow sensor to be calibrated are recorded with high temporal resolution during the LDV measurements.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The measurement deviation of the flow sensors (calibration object) is determined by comparing the volume flow determined using the LDV method and the time-averaged value of the flow sensors during the measurement time.
[src:flow-sensors/flow-measurement] The best accredited measurement uncertainty for water (5°C to 150°C) is 0.7 %.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] A **mass flow meter**, also known as an **inertial flow meter**, is a device that measures mass flow rate of a fluid traveling through a tube.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The mass flow rate is the mass of the fluid traveling past a fixed point per unit time.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The mass flow meter does not measure the volume per unit time (e.g. cubic meters per second) passing through the device; it measures the mass per unit time (e.g. kilograms per second) flowing through the device.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] Volumetric flow rate is the mass flow rate divided by the fluid density.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] If the density is constant, then the relationship is simple.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] If the fluid has varying density, then the relationship is not simple.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] For example, the density of the fluid may change with temperature, pressure, or composition.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The fluid may also be a combination of phases such as a fluid with entrained bubbles.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] Actual density can be determined due to dependency of sound velocity on the controlled liquid concentration.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The Coriolis flow meter is based on the Coriolis force, which bends rotating objects depending on their velocity.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] There are two basic configurations of Coriolis flow meter: the *curved tube flow meter* and the *straight tube flow meter*.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] This article discusses the curved tube design.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The animations on the right do not represent an actually existing Coriolis flow meter design.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The purpose of the animations is to illustrate the operating principle, and to show the connection with rotation.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] Fluid is being pumped through the mass flow meter.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] When there is mass flow, the tube twists slightly.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The arm through which fluid flows away from the axis of rotation must exert a force on the fluid, to increase its angular momentum, so it bends backwards.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The arm through which fluid is pushed back to the axis of rotation must exert a force on the fluid to decrease the fluid's angular momentum again, hence that arm will bend forward.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] In other words, the inlet arm (containing an outwards directed flow), is lagging behind the overall rotation, the part which in rest is parallel to the axis is now skewed, and the outlet arm (containing an inwards directed flow) leads the overall rotation.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The animation on the right represents how curved tube mass flow meters are designed.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The fluid is led through two parallel tubes.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] An actuator (not shown) induces equal counter vibrations on the sections parallel to the axis, to make the measuring device less sensitive to outside vibrations.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The actual frequency of the vibration depends on the size of the mass flow meter, and ranges from 80 to 1000 Hz.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The amplitude of the vibration is too small to be seen, but it can be felt by touch.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] When no fluid is flowing, the motion of the two tubes is symmetrical, as shown in the left animation.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The animation on the right illustrates what happens during mass flow: some twisting of the tubes.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The arm carrying the flow away from the axis of rotation must exert a force on the fluid to accelerate the flowing mass to the vibrating speed of the tubes at the outside (increase of absolute angular momentum), so it is lagging behind the overall vibration.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The arm through which fluid is pushed back towards the axis of movement must exert a force on the fluid to decrease the fluid's absolute angular speed (angular momentum) again, hence that arm leads the overall vibration.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The inlet arm and the outlet arm vibrate with the same frequency as the overall vibration, but when there is mass flow the two vibrations are out of sync: the inlet arm is behind, the outlet arm is ahead.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The two vibrations are shifted in phase with respect to each other, and the degree of phase-shift is a measure for the amount of mass that is flowing through the tubes and line.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] where *Ku* is the temperature dependent stiffness of the tube, *K* is a shape-dependent factor, *d* is the width, *τ* is the time lag, *ω* is the vibration frequency, and *Iu* is the inertia of the tube.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] As the inertia of the tube depend on its contents, knowledge of the fluid density is needed for the calculation of an accurate mass flow rate.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] If the density changes too often for manual calibration to be sufficient, the Coriolis flow meter can be adapted to measure the density as well.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] The natural vibration frequency of the flow tubes depends on the combined mass of the tube and the fluid contained in it.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] By setting the tube in motion and measuring the natural frequency, the mass of the fluid contained in the tube can be deduced.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] Dividing the mass on the known volume of the tube gives us the *density* of the fluid.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] An instantaneous density measurement allows the calculation of flow in volume per time by dividing mass flow with density.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] Both mass flow and density measurements depend on the vibration of the tube.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] Calibration is affected by changes in the rigidity of the flow tubes.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] Changes in temperature and pressure will cause the tube rigidity to change, but these can be compensated for through pressure and temperature zero and span compensation factors.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] Additional effects on tube rigidity will cause shifts in the calibration factor over time due to degradation of the flow tubes.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] These effects include pitting, cracking, coating, erosion or corrosion.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] It is not possible to compensate for these changes dynamically, but efforts to monitor the effects may be made through regular meter calibration or verification checks.
[src:flow-sensors/mass-flow-meter] If a change is deemed to have occurred, but is considered to be acceptable, the offset may be added to the existing calibration factor to ensure continued accurate measurement.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] An **orifice plate** is a device used for measuring flow rate, reducing pressure or restricting flow (in the latter two cases it is often called a **restriction plate**).
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] An orifice plate is a thin plate with a hole in it, which is usually placed in a pipe.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] When a fluid (whether liquid or gaseous) passes through the orifice, its pressure builds up slightly upstream of the orifice but as the fluid is forced to converge to pass through the hole, the velocity increases and the fluid pressure decreases.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] A little downstream of the orifice the flow reaches its point of maximum convergence, the *vena contracta* (see drawing to the right) where the velocity reaches its maximum and the pressure reaches its minimum.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Beyond that, the flow expands, the velocity falls and the pressure increases.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] By measuring the difference in fluid pressure across tappings upstream and downstream of the plate, the flow rate can be obtained from Bernoulli's equation using coefficients established from extensive research.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The overall pressure loss in the pipe due to an orifice plate is lower than the measured differential pressure, typically by a factor of $1-\beta ^{1.9}$ .
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Under these circumstances and when the orifice plate is constructed and installed according to appropriate standards, the flow rate can easily be determined using published formulae based on substantial research and published in industry, national and international standards.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] An orifice plate is called a **calibrated orifice** if it has been calibrated with an appropriate fluid flow and a traceable flow measurement device.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Plates are commonly made with sharp-edged circular orifices and installed concentric with the pipe and with pressure tappings at one of three standard pairs of distances upstream and downstream of the plate; these types are covered by ISO 5167 and other major standards.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The edges may be rounded or conical, the plate may have an orifice the same size as the pipe except for a segment at top or bottom which is obstructed, the orifice may be installed eccentric to the pipe, and the pressure tappings may be at other positions.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Variations on these possibilities are covered in various standards and handbooks.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Each combination gives rise to different coefficients of discharge which can be predicted so long as various conditions are met, conditions which differ from one type to another.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Once the orifice plate is designed and installed, the flow rate can often be indicated with an acceptably low uncertainty simply by taking the square root of the differential pressure across the orifice's pressure tappings and applying an appropriate constant.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Orifice plates are also used to reduce pressure or restrict flow, in which case they are often called restriction plates.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] These types are covered by ISO 5167 and other major standards.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The measured differential pressure differs for each combination and so the coefficient of discharge used in flow calculations depends partly on the tapping positions.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The simplest installations use single tappings upstream and downstream, but in some circumstances these may be unreliable; they might be blocked by solids or gas-bubbles, or the flow profile might be uneven so that the pressures at the tappings are higher or lower than the average in those planes.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] In these situations multiple tappings can be used, arranged circumferentially around the pipe and joined by a piezometer ring, or (in the case of corner taps) annular slots running completely round the internal circumference of the orifice carrier.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Standards and handbooks are mainly concerned with **sharp-edged thin** plates.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] In these, the leading edge is sharp and free of burrs and the cylindrical section of the orifice is short, either because the entire plate is thin or because the downstream edge of the plate is bevelled.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Exceptions include the **quarter-circle** or **quadrant-edge** orifice, which has a fully rounded leading edge and no cylindrical section, and the **conical inlet** or **conical entrance** plate which has a bevelled leading edge and a very short cylindrical section.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The orifices are normally concentric with the pipe (the **eccentric** orifice is a specific exception) and circular (except in the specific case of the **segmental** or **chord** orifice, in which the plate obstructs just a segment of the pipe).
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Standards and handbooks stipulate that the upstream surface of the plate is particularly flat and smooth.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Standards and handbooks stipulate a well-developed flow profile; velocities will be lower at the pipe wall than in the centre but not eccentric or jetting.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Similarly the flow downstream of the plate must be unobstructed, otherwise the downstream pressure will be affected.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] To achieve this, the pipe must be acceptably circular, smooth and straight for stipulated distances.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Sometimes when it is impossible to provide enough straight pipe, flow conditioners such as tube bundles or plates with multiple holes are inserted into the pipe to straighten and develop the flow profile, but even these require a further length of straight pipe before the orifice itself.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Some standards and handbooks also provide for flows from or into large spaces rather than pipes, stipulating that the region before or after the plate is free of obstruction and abnormalities in the flow.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The above expression for $q_{v}^{'}$ gives the theoretical volume flow rate.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Deriving the above equations used the cross-section of the orifice opening and is not as realistic as using the minimum cross-section at the vena contracta.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] In addition, frictional losses may not be negligible and viscosity and turbulence effects may be present.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] For that reason, the coefficient of discharge $C_{d}$ is introduced.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Methods exist for determining the coefficient of discharge as a function of the Reynolds number.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The parameter ${\frac {1}{\sqrt {1-\beta ^{4}}}}$ is often referred to as the *velocity of approach factor* and multiplying the coefficient of discharge by that parameter (as was done above) produces the flow coefficient C .
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Methods also exist for determining the flow coefficient as a function of the beta $\beta$ and the location of the downstream pressure sensing tap.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] For rough approximations, the flow coefficient may be assumed to be between 0.60 and 0.75.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] For a first approximation, a flow coefficient of 0.62 can be used as this approximates to fully developed flow.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] An orifice only works well when supplied with a fully developed flow profile.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] This is achieved by a long upstream length (20 to 40 pipe diameters, depending on Reynolds number) or the use of a flow conditioner.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Orifice plates are small and inexpensive but do not recover the pressure drop as well as a venturi, nozzle, or venturi-nozzle does.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Venturis also require much less straight pipe upstream.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] A venturi meter is more efficient, but usually more expensive and less accurate (unless calibrated in a laboratory) than an orifice plate.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] In general, equation (2) is applicable only for incompressible flows.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] It can be modified by introducing the expansibility factor, (also called the expansion factor) $\epsilon$ to account for the compressibility of gasses.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] $\epsilon$ is 1.0 for incompressible fluids and it can be calculated for compressible gases using empirically determined formulae as shown below in computation.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] For smaller values of β (such as restriction plates with β less than 0.25 and discharge from tanks), if the fluid is compressible, the rate of flow depends on whether the flow has become choked.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] Flow rates through an orifice plate can be calculated without specifically calibrating the individual flowmeter so long as the construction and installation of the device complies with the stipulations of the relevant standard or handbook.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The calculation takes account of the fluid and fluid conditions, the pipe size, the orifice size and the measured differential pressure; it also takes account of the coefficient of discharge of the orifice plate, which depends upon the orifice type and the positions of the pressure tappings.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] With local pressure tappings (corner, flange and D+D/2), sharp-edged orifices have coefficients around 0.6 to 0.63, while the coefficients for conical entrance plates are in the range 0.73 to 0.734 and for quarter-circle plates 0.77 to 0.85.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The coefficients of sharp-edged orifices vary more with fluids and flow rates than the coefficients of conical-entrance and quarter-circle plates, especially at low flows and high viscosities.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] For compressible flows such as flows of gases or steam, an *expansibility factor* or *expansion factor* is also calculated.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] This factor is primarily a function of the ratio of the measured differential pressure to the fluid pressure and so can vary significantly as the flow rate varies, especially at high differential pressures and low static pressures.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The equations below largely follow the notation of the international standard ISO 5167 and use SI units.
[src:flow-sensors/orifice-plate] The overall pressure loss caused by an orifice plate is less than the differential pressure measured across tappings near the plate.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] A **rotameter** is a device that measures the volumetric flow rate of fluid in a closed tube.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] It belongs to a class of meters called variable-area flowmeters, which measure flow rate by allowing the cross-sectional area the fluid travels through to vary, causing a measurable effect.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] The first variable area meter with rotating float was invented by Karl Kueppers (1874–1933) in Aachen in 1908.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] This is described in the German patent 215225.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] Felix Meyer founded the company "*Deutsche Rotawerke GmbH*" in Aachen recognizing the fundamental importance of this invention.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] They improved this invention with new shapes of the float and of the glass tube.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] Kueppers invented the special shape for the inside of the glass tube that realized a symmetrical flow scale.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] The brand name Rotameter was registered by the British company GEC Elliot automation, Rotameter Co.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] In many other countries the brand name Rotameter is registered by Rota Yokogawa GmbH & Co.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] KG in Germany which is now owned by Yokogawa Electric Corp.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] A rotameter consists of a tapered tube, typically made of glass with a 'float' (a shaped weight, made either of anodized aluminum or a ceramic) inside, that is pushed up by the drag force of the flow and pulled down by gravity.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] The drag force for a given fluid and float cross section is a function of flow speed squared only, see drag equation.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] A higher volumetric flow rate through a given area increases flow speed and drag force, so the float will be pushed upwards.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] However, as the inside of the rotameter is cone shaped (widens), the area around the float through which the medium flows increases as the float rises, and thus the flow speed and drag force decrease until there is mechanical equilibrium with the float's weight.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] Floats are made in many different shapes, with spheres and ellipsoids being the most common.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] The float may be diagonally grooved and partially colored so that it rotates axially as the fluid passes.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] This shows if the float is stuck since it will only rotate if it is free.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] Readings are usually taken at the top of the widest part of the float; the center for an ellipsoid, or the top for a cylinder.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] Some manufacturers use a different standard.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] The "float" must not float in the fluid: it has to have a higher density than the fluid, otherwise it will float to the top even if there is no flow.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] The mechanical nature of the measuring principle provides a flow measurement device that does not require any electrical power.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] If the tube is made of metal, the float position is transferred to an external indicator via a magnetic coupling.
[src:flow-sensors/rotameter] This capability has considerably expanded the range of applications for the variable area flowmeter, since the measurement can observed remotely from the process or used for automatic control.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] In the case of the thermal dispersion, or immersible, type of flow meter, the heat is transferred to the boundary layer of the fluid flowing over the heated surface.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] In the case of the capillary-tube type, the heat is transferred to the bulk of the fluid flowing through a small heated capillary tube.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] The principles of operation of the two types are both thermal in nature, but are so substantially different that two separate standards are required.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] Additionally, their applications are much different.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] Thermal dispersion flow meters are commonly used for general industrial gas flow applications in pipes and ducts, whereas capillary types are primarily used for smaller flows of clean gases or liquids in tubes.This type is most widely used for thermal mass flow meters in industry.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] Nevertheless, the capillary type is not the subject of this discussion.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] The operation of thermal dispersion mass flow meters is attributed to L.V.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] King who, in 1914, published his famous King's Law revealing how a heated wire immersed in a fluid flow measures the mass velocity at a point in the flow.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] King called his instrument a "hot-wire anemometer".
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] However, it was not until the 1960s and 1970s that industrial-grade thermal dispersion mass flow meters finally emerged.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] The primary reason thermal mass flow meters are popular in industrial applications is the way they are designed and built.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] They feature no moving parts, nearly unobstructed straight through flow path, require no temperature or pressure corrections and retain accuracy over a wide range of flow rates.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] Straight pipe runs can be reduced by using dual-plate flow conditioning elements.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] Thermal mass flow meters are typically used in low flow conditions because the amount of heat required for an effective measurement is proportional to flow rate.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] However, in many applications, the thermal properties of the fluid can be dependent upon fluid composition.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] In such applications, varying composition of the fluid during actual operation can affect the thermal flow measurement.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] Therefore, it is important for the thermal flow meter supplier to know the composition of the fluid so that the proper calibration factor can be used to determine the flow rate accurately.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] Suppliers can provide appropriate calibration information for other gas mixtures, however the accuracy of the thermal flow meter is dependent on the actual gas mixture being the same as the gas mixture used for calibration purposes.
[src:flow-sensors/thermal-mass-flow-meter] In other words, the accuracy of a thermal flow meter calibrated for a given gas mixture will be degraded if the actual flowing gas has a different composition.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The **Venturi effect** is the reduction in fluid pressure that results when a moving fluid speeds up as it is funneled from one section of a pipe to another, smaller section.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] As the fluid flows into a smaller area, the fluid's velocity increases, while the static pressure decreases.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The Venturi effect is an example of Bernoulli's principle.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The Venturi effect is named after its discoverer, the Italian Physicist Giovanni Battista Venturi, and was first published in 1797.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The effect has various applications in engineering, architecture, and everyday objects such as atomizer nozzles and wine aerators.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The reduction in pressure inside the constriction can be used both for measuring the fluid flow and for moving other fluids (e.g. in a vacuum ejector).
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] Thus, any gain in kinetic energy a fluid may attain by its increased velocity through a constriction is balanced by a drop in pressure because of its loss in potential energy.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] By measuring the pressure difference without needing to measure the actual pressures at the two points, the flow rate can be determined, as in various flow measurement devices such as Venturi meters, Venturi nozzles and orifice plates.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] where $\rho$ is the density of the fluid, $v_{1}$ is the (slower) fluid velocity where the pipe is wider, and $v_{2}$ is the (faster) fluid velocity where the pipe is narrower (as seen in the figure).
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The static pressure at each position is measured using a small tube either outside and ending at the wall or into the pipe with the small tube end face parallel with the flow direction.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The limiting case of the Venturi effect is when a fluid reaches the state of choked flow, where the fluid velocity approaches the local speed of sound of the fluid.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] When a fluid system is in a state of choked flow, a further decrease in the downstream pressure environment will not lead to an increase in velocity, unless the fluid is compressed.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The mass flow rate for a compressible fluid will increase with increased upstream pressure, which will increase the density of the fluid through the constriction (though the velocity will remain constant).
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] This is the principle of operation of a de Laval nozzle.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] Increasing source temperature can also increase the local sonic velocity, thus allowing increased mass flow rate.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The Bernoulli equation is invertible, and pressure should rise when a fluid slows down.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] Nevertheless, if there is a shortening expansion in the tube section, turbulence is more likely to appear, and the variation from the theorem will increase.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] Generally in Venturi tubes, the pressure in the entrance is compared to the pressure in the middle section and the output section is not compared with them.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The simplest apparatus is a tubular setup known as a Venturi tube or simply a Venturi (plural: "Venturis" or occasionally "Venturies").
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] Fluid first flows through a length of converging tube and then often flows into a diverging tube.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] To avoid undue aerodynamic drag, a Venturi tube typically has an entry cone of 30 degrees and an exit cone of 5 degrees.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] Venturi tubes are often used in processes where permanent pressure loss is not tolerable and where maximum accuracy is needed in case of highly viscous liquids.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] Venturi tubes are more expensive to construct than simple orifice plates, and both function on the same basic principle.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] However, for any given differential pressure, orifice plates cause significantly more permanent energy loss.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] Both Venturi tubes and orifice plates are used in industrial applications and in scientific laboratories for measuring the flow rate of liquids.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] A Venturi can be used to measure the volumetric flow rate, $\scriptstyle Q$ , using Bernoulli's principle.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] At the end of the system, a mixture of liquid and gas will appear.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] See aspirator and pressure head for discussion of this type of siphon.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] As fluid flows through a Venturi, the expansion and compression of the fluids cause the pressure inside the Venturi to change.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] This principle can be used in metrology for gauges calibrated for differential pressures.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] This type of pressure measurement may be more convenient, for example, to measure fuel or combustion pressures in jet or rocket engines.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] The first large-scale Venturi meters to measure liquid flows were developed by Clemens Herschel who used them to measure small and large flows of water and wastewater beginning at the end of the 19th century.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] Fundamentally, pressure-based meters measure kinetic energy density.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] where constant terms are absorbed into *k*.
[src:flow-sensors/venturi-effect] However, measurements outside the design point must compensate for the effects of temperature, pressure, and molar mass on density and concentration.
